{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-02058/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-02058"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:20:58"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["medium shot"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["low"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["mobile, pan, tracking"]}},{"label":{"none":["Lighting"]},"value":{"none":["backlighting"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["two shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A man sets his hands on a table adorned with photographs as he looks at a woman standing next to him."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02058/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-02058","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02058/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-02058"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02058/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02058/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02058/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02058/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02058/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02058/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02058/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02058/canvas/1/97ebae6e-beba-45fb-a472-105ddc0bae84","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-07-01T15:30:47.988Z","creator":"Clara Smith","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>As Reynolds tells Alma about his childhood and how he became a dressmaker, the camera pushes in slowly, as if trying to listen in on the intimacies that he is sharing. According to Trent Ludwig, “this scene rather bluntly shows that the significance attributed to the wedding dress Reynolds made for his mother has been withdrawn from the original dress. In this withdrawal, the wedding dress became a virtual object in Reynolds’ memory, which holds the significance that was once held by the actual, original dress (Deleuze, 101–102). This virtual dress is incorporated into the actual dress Reynolds is producing, thus repeatedly transferring the virtual signification onto the dress currently in production (Deleuze, 101–102). In this way, each successive Woodcock dress is a repetition of the Mother’s wedding dress and each wearer a new substitute for the Mother. Even if the wearer of the dress is not taken as a sexual partner, they still inhabit that zone of significance for Reynolds” (Ludwig, “Threading Between Dresses and Debts,” 166).</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02058/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:200.17621145374454,147.22466960352415,792.9735682819382,892.6982378854626"}}}]}]}]}